  "prompt": "What does the @ symbol do in Excel?",
  "response": "In Excel, the @ symbol has a few specific uses:\n\n1. In formulas with structured references (tables):\n- When referencing a column in a table, the @ symbol means \"current row\"\n- Example: =[@Sales] would refer to the Sales column in the current row of a table\n\n2. In dynamic array formulas (Excel 365):\n- It can help specify which cells to reference in certain array operations\n- Helps with spilling and dynamic range selection\n\n3. In newer Excel versions with dynamic arrays:\n- Can help clarify row or column references in some complex formulas\n\nHowever, for most everyday Excel users, the @ symbol isn't frequently used and many people won't encounter it in typical spreadsheet work.",
